"{\n  \"text\": \"One of the things that I think is very positive and very encouraging when you look at the history of agriculture is the contribution of Chinese agriculture. I learned about through F. H. King, Farmers of Forty Centuries, but it was also brought up in some of the Albert Howard I like so much. And it's essentially the idea that China, in heavy population density, without changing lands, continuously farmed soil in such a way that they didn't lose fertility over 4,000 years. This was something that the Europeans and many of the uh other parts of the world uh could not manage to do. And so some of these early authors of the regenerative period went to China to go figure out what's going on. Like F. H. King's book was based on a tour deal, I think that was 1905, just to give you timeline. And what he found was that they had a system of canals that connected the population centers to the farm areas. And they would put all of the debris of society, but the countryside and everything else in these canals, and with a series of manual foot pumps, send this stuff down to the farmlands with water into a muck, but it was composting, so it wouldn't have been smelly or anything like that. There would have been a lot of carbon matter in this muck going down. And then at the end of the season or just whenever I guess uh they would the water would recede, they would stop the pumps, the debris that was down into the field areas they would drag onto the fields and they would compost. And this heavy nitrogen composting uh debris matter was fantastic fertilizer. And what they could do with you know the law of returns is the what they were taking off the crops or off the fields, they could just add back to it so they could do continuous crops that were heavy depletion without having to let the field go fallow or do any other methods that take time to replenish the carbon in the field. They could just use this canal method that was utilizing the waste from the cities, the waste, sending it down to the farmlands where it became processed into fertility. And if you think about that for a second, and our modern technology and how easy it would be to divert our waste out of this centralized process where we process it into big, heavily dense, toxic logs, but just to actually disperse it into farmlands where it is properly broken down, but where it is turned into fertility, where it's turned into organic matter so that you don't need to use fertilizers and pesticides, and you have to use less water where uh you can improve the soil and get the biological churning that we need so bad in our soils to start going. Anyway, thanks, y'all.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" One of the things that I think is very positive and very encouraging when you look at the history of agriculture is the contribution of Chinese agriculture.\",\n      \"start\": 0.64,\n      \"end\": 9.92,\n      \"duration\": 9.28,\n      \"confidence\": 0.999,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" O\",\n          \"start\": 0.64,\n          \"end\": 0.8,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 0.997\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ne\",\n          \"start\": 0.8,\n          \"end\": 0.96,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" of\",\n          \"start\": 0.96,\n          \"end\": 1.12,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" the\",\n          \"start\": 1.12,\n          \"end\": 1.28,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" th\",\n          \"start\": 1.28,\n          \"end\": 1.44,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ings\",\n          \"start\": 1.44,\n          \"end\": 1.6,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\"